3. If `theme.colors` is non-empty, iterate and call `document.documentElement.style.setProperty('--' + key, value)`.
4. Handle `fontFamily` / `fontSize` overrides on `document.body` if present.
5. Apply `no-transitions` class and removal, same as today.

**Resolving `"system"`:** When the stored value is `"system"`, resolve to `t3-light` or `t3-dark` based on `window.matchMedia("(prefers-color-scheme: dark)")`.

**New snapshot type:**

```typescript
type ThemeSnapshot = {
  themeId: string;        // raw stored value, "system" | theme ID
  systemDark: boolean;
};
```

**New return type:**

```typescript
{
  theme: string;                           // raw stored value ("system" | theme ID)
  setTheme: (id: string) => void;
  resolvedTheme: "light" | "dark";         // BACKWARD COMPATIBLE
  activeTheme: ThemeDefinition;            // the fully resolved ThemeDefinition object
  availableThemes: readonly ThemeDefinition[];
}
```

The `resolvedTheme` derivation is: `activeTheme.mode`.

The existing call sites only destructure `{ theme, setTheme, resolvedTheme }`, so they all continue to work without changes. The old type `Theme = "light" | "dark" | "system"` is widened to `string`. The settings page currently passes `option.value` which are `"system"`, `"light"`, `"dark"` -- these will need to map to `"system"`, `"t3-light"`, `"t3-dark"`. This mapping is handled in Step 5.

**Migration logic in `getStored()`:** If the stored value is `"light"`, map it to `"t3-light"`. If `"dark"`, map it to `"t3-dark"`. This provides seamless migration for existing users.

#### Step 4: Create `apps/web/src/components/ThemeSelector.tsx`

A new component that renders a grid of theme preview swatches. It follows the existing UI patterns from the settings page.

**Structure:**

```typescript
import { listThemes, type ThemeDefinition } from "@t3tools/shared/themes";
import { useTheme } from "../hooks/useTheme";

function ThemeSwatch({ theme, selected, onSelect }: {
  theme: ThemeDefinition;
  selected: boolean;
  onSelect: () => void;
}) {
  // Renders a small rectangle showing the theme's key colors
  // (background, foreground, primary, accent)
  // Uses inline styles derived from theme.colors (or hardcoded
  // values for t3-light/t3-dark since their colors map is empty)
}

export function ThemeSelector() {
  const { theme, setTheme, availableThemes } = useTheme();
  // Renders the "system" option as a special card
  // Renders each theme as a ThemeSwatch in a grid
  // <div className="grid grid-cols-3 gap-3">
  //   <SystemThemeCard />
  //   {availableThemes.map(t => <ThemeSwatch ... />)}
  // </div>
}
```

The swatch preview shows 4-5 color dots or a mini rectangle with the theme's `background`, `foreground`, `primary`, and `accent` colors. For `t3-light` and `t3-dark` whose `colors` map is empty, the swatch uses hardcoded preview colors that match what `index.css` defines (e.g. `#ffffff` background for light, the neutral-950 mix for dark).

A helper constant `SWATCH_PREVIEW_COLORS` in the component maps theme IDs to preview color tuples for built-in themes, falling back to `theme.colors` for custom ones.

#### Step 5: Update `apps/web/src/routes/_chat.settings.tsx`

Replace the existing Appearance section's radio-button group with the new `ThemeSelector` component.

**Changes:**

1. Remove the `THEME_OPTIONS` constant (lines 25-41).
2. Replace the radio button group inside the Appearance `<section>` with `<ThemeSelector />`.
3. The `useTheme()` destructuring on line 90 stays the same -- `{ theme, setTheme, resolvedTheme }` still works.
4. The "Active theme" display at line 241 can be enhanced to show `activeTheme.name` instead of just `resolvedTheme`, but `resolvedTheme` also still works.

The import changes from just `useTheme` to also importing `ThemeSelector`:

```typescript
import { ThemeSelector } from "../components/ThemeSelector";
```

#### Step 6: Handle CSS variable cleanup

The rewritten `applyThemeDefinition` function must track which CSS properties it has set so it can clean them up when switching themes. This is important because switching from `t3-midnight` (which sets many inline styles) to `t3-dark` (which sets none) must remove all the midnight overrides.

Implementation detail in `useTheme.ts`:

```typescript
let appliedCssPropertyKeys: Set<string> = new Set();

function applyThemeDefinition(theme: ThemeDefinition, suppressTransitions: boolean) {
  if (suppressTransitions) {
    document.documentElement.classList.add("no-transitions");
  }

  // Toggle dark class
  document.documentElement.classList.toggle("dark", theme.mode === "dark");

  // Clear previously applied inline overrides
  for (const key of appliedCssPropertyKeys) {
    document.documentElement.style.removeProperty(`--${key}`);
  }
  appliedCssPropertyKeys.clear();

  // Apply new overrides
  for (const [key, value] of Object.entries(theme.colors)) {
    if (value !== undefined) {
      document.documentElement.style.setProperty(`--${key}`, value);
      appliedCssPropertyKeys.add(key);
    }
  }

  // Font overrides
  if (theme.fontFamily !== undefined) {
    document.body.style.setProperty("font-family", theme.fontFamily);
    appliedCssPropertyKeys.add("__fontFamily");
  } else {
    document.body.style.removeProperty("font-family");
  }
  if (theme.fontSize !== undefined) {
    document.documentElement.style.setProperty("font-size", theme.fontSize);
    appliedCssPropertyKeys.add("__fontSize");
  } else {
    document.documentElement.style.removeProperty("font-size");
  }

  if (suppressTransitions) {
    void document.documentElement.offsetHeight; // force reflow
    requestAnimationFrame(() => {
      document.documentElement.classList.remove("no-transitions");
    });
  }
}
```

#### Step 7: Verify no changes needed in consuming components

Each file that consumes `useTheme()` only uses `resolvedTheme` (type `"light" | "dark"`). Since the new hook preserves this field and its type, the following files require zero changes:

- `apps/web/src/components/DiffWorkerPoolProvider.tsx` -- uses `resolvedTheme` to call `resolveDiffThemeName()`
- `apps/web/src/components/DiffPanel.tsx` -- uses `resolvedTheme` for cache keys and diff rendering
